<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">📖 Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Two big moves today. The signature U5 partner lands.</p>
  <p><strong>First move: stakeholder analysis basics.</strong> The 6-field framework (Who They Are / What They Want / Evidence They Cite / Position / Power / Allies+Opponents) is how you map a real water dispute. The key insight: real stakeholders don't argue from the same evidence — they cite <em>different</em> evidence because their <em>interests</em> differ. Stakeholder mapping is <strong>interest-first, evidence-second</strong>. A Tamil Nadu delta farmer and a Karnataka upstream farmer don't agree on what the rainfall data means because they don't have the same interest in what the data should imply.</p>
  <p><strong>Second move: <a href="/ai-partners/stakeholder-voice/">The Stakeholder Voice</a> AI partner is introduced.</strong> The signature U5 partner. It role-plays the <em>strongest</em> version of any stakeholder you name. Making the strongest counter-argument is the move — students rehearse responding to well-formed positions, not to caricatures. The trial-arm split lands today: each section starts a slightly different scaffold (see Interact card below). All three sections are working on the same skill: <strong>perspective-taking</strong>, the year's T/T centerpiece.</p>
  <p>Counter-argument work runs through the whole block. By exit: you've stated the strongest counter to your stakeholder's position <em>fairly</em>, then responded <em>without strawmanning</em>. This is the move the Position Paper's "Acknowledge competing concerns" section needs.</p>
</section>

